\begin_layout Problem*
Prove 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=-AC\{D,B\}+A\{C,B\}D-C\{D,A\}B+\{C,A\}DB.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
By definition, we have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=ABCD-CDAB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
But 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B,C\}=BC+CB\implies BC=\{B,C\}-CB$
\end_inset

, and we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B,C\}=\{C,B\}$
\end_inset

, therefore, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ABCD=A(\{C,B\}-CB)D=A\{C,B\}D-ACBD
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Putting into the main equation, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=A\{C,B\}D-ACBD-CDAB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now, let's work with the 
\begin_inset Formula $ACBD$
\end_inset

 term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
BD=\{B,D\}-DB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Therefore, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ACBD=AC(\{B,D\}-DB)=AC\{B,D\}-ACDB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Again, inserting this into the main equation, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=A\{C,B\}D-AC\{B,D\}+ACDB-CDAB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now, for 
\begin_inset Formula $ACDB$
\end_inset

 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
AC=\{C,A\}-CA
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Then, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ACDB=(\{C,A\}-CA)DB=\{C,A\}DB-CADB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
And again, inserting into the main equation, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=A\{C,B\}D-AC\{B,D\}+\{C,A\}DB-CADB-CDAB
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
But in the last expression, the last two therms on the rhs, could be written
 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CADB+ADAB=C\{D,A\}B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Therefore, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[AB,CD]=A\{C,B\}D-AC\{B,D\}+\{C,A\}DB-C\{D,A\}B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Just as we wanted to prove.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the orthonormality of 
\begin_inset Formula $|+\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|-\rangle$
\end_inset

, prove 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem*
Suppose a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\text{x}2$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}$
\end_inset

 (not necessarily Hermitian, nor unitary) is written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}=a_{0}\mathbb{I}+\hat{\sigma}\cdot\mathbf{a}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1,2,3}$
\end_inset

 are just numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing single
\align block
How are 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}\ \left(k=1,2,3\right)$
\end_inset

 related to 
\begin_inset Formula $tr(\hat{X})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $tr(\sigma_{k}\hat{X})$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\paragraph_spacing single
\align block
Obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Let's work with the first part of the problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
We know that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\{x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

 represent the Pauli matrices, and those are represented in the eigenbase
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}$
\end_inset

 as the following 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{x}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right),\ \sigma_{y}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{array}\right),\ \sigma_{z}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right).\label{eq:01}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
And we also know that for those matrices the following relationship holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}=\delta_{ij}+i\epsilon_{ijk}\sigma_{k}.\label{eq:SigmaSigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Thus, for part 
\series bold
1)
\series default
, we have the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}=a_{0}\delta_{ij}+\sigma_{k}a_{k},\ \text{with}\ i,j=1,2,\ k=1,2,3\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\hat{X}=a_{0}\delta_{ij}+\sigma_{1}a_{1}+\sigma_{2}a_{2}+\sigma_{3}a_{3}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Now, if we do the following identification, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}=\sigma_{x},\ \sigma_{2}=\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{3}=\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{X}=a_{0}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{x}+a_{2}\sigma_{y}+a_{3}\sigma_{z}\text{,}\label{eq:02}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
or in matrix notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}=a_{0}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)+a_{1}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right)+a_{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{array}\right)+a_{3}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\implies\hat{X}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a_{0}+a_{3} & a_{1}-ia_{2}\\
a_{1}+ia_{2} & a_{0}-a_{3}
\end{array}\right)\text{.}\label{eq:03}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Now, for the tr(
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X})$
\end_inset

, let's take a look at the equations given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and note that all the Pauli matrices are traceless, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{i})=0\ \forall i=x,y,z\ \text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
then, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\hat{X})=tr\left(a_{0}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{x}+a_{2}\sigma_{y}+a_{3}\sigma_{z}\right)=a_{0}tr(\delta_{ij})+a_{1}tr(\sigma_{x})+a_{2}tr(\sigma_{y})+a_{3}tr(\sigma_{z})\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies tr(\hat{X})=a_{0}tr(\delta_{ij})=a_{0}\delta_{ii}=2a_{0}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ tr(\hat{X})=2a_{0}
\]

\end_inset

Now, for the 
\begin_inset Formula $tr(\sigma_{k}\hat{X})$
\end_inset

, we have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{k}\hat{X}=a_{0}\sigma_{k}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{k}\sigma_{1}+a_{2}\sigma_{k}\sigma_{2}+a_{3}\sigma_{k}\sigma_{3}\text{, with }k=1,2,3\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Or, in component form, writing explicitly the products, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{1}\hat{X}=a_{0}\sigma_{1}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}+a_{2}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}+a_{3}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}\text{,}\label{eq:04}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{2}\hat{X}=a_{0}\sigma_{2}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{1}+a_{2}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{2}+a_{3}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}\text{ and }\label{eq:05}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{3}\hat{X}=a_{0}\sigma_{3}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{3}\sigma_{1}+a_{2}\sigma_{3}\sigma_{2}+a_{3}\sigma_{3}\sigma_{3}\text{,}\label{eq:06}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, if we write the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{k}\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 in matrix form, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}\delta_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right),\ \sigma_{2}\delta_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\ \text{and}\ \sigma_{3}\delta_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right),$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{1}\delta_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\text{,}\ \sigma_{2}\delta_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\ \text{and}\ \sigma_{3}\delta_{ij}=\sigma_{3}.\label{eq:07}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of doing the calculation for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, using matrices, let's use the property shown in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SigmaSigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and for a better reading, let's write it down again:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}=\delta_{ij}+i\epsilon_{ijk}\sigma_{k}
\]

\end_inset

In general 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

 it's a 3-rank tensor totally asntisymetric, but for the purposes of the
 following calculations, we are going to consider it just a constant which
 depends on the order of the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

, and its value could be 
\begin_inset Formula $0,1\text{ o }-1$
\end_inset

.
 Now, having said that, for our purposes, let's make 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=i\epsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, in general, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ijk}\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset

 is just another Pauli matrix, and let's call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 it's different from the actual values of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (and we do that for the properties of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ijk}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, with the previous statements, and with the changes of variables,
 we have the following
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}=\delta_{ij}+\alpha\sigma_{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, if we take the trace of the previous expression, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j})=tr\left(\delta_{ij}+\alpha\sigma_{\alpha}\right)=tr(\delta_{ij})+\alpha tr(\sigma_{\alpha})=tr(\delta_{ij})\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

In other words, the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

 is not zero if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Now, with the previous result, and with the equations given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and applying this to the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 y 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we got
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{1}\hat{X})=tr\left(a_{0}\sigma_{1}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}+a_{2}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}+a_{3}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}\right)=tr\left(a_{0}\sigma_{1}\delta_{ij}+a_{1}\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies tr(\sigma_{1}\hat{X})=a_{1}tr\left(\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}\right)=a_{1}tr(\delta_{11})=2a_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ tr(\sigma_{1}\hat{X})=2a_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Noe, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{2}\hat{X}$
\end_inset

, we got
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{2}\hat{X})=tr\left(a_{0}\sigma_{2}\delta_{ij}+a_{2}\sigma_{2}\sigma_{2}\right)=a_{2}tr(\sigma_{2}\sigma_{2})=a_{2}tr(\delta_{22})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies tr(\sigma_{2}\hat{X})=2a_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

And finally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{3}\hat{X}$
\end_inset

, we got
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{3}\hat{X})=tr\left(a_{0}\sigma_{3}\delta_{ij}+a_{3}\sigma_{3}\sigma_{3}\right)=a_{0}tr(\sigma_{3})+a_{3}tr(\sigma_{33})=2a_{3}tr(\delta_{33}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies tr(\sigma_{3}\hat{X})=2a_{3}tr(\delta_{33}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Therefore, we end with the following result if 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,3$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(\sigma_{k}\hat{X})=2a_{k}.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\series bold
2)
\series default
, let's focus on the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
It's clear that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}_{11}+\hat{X}_{22}=a_{0}+a_{3}+a_{0}-a_{3}=2a_{0}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ a_{0}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{X}_{11}+\hat{X}_{22}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}_{12}+\hat{X}_{21}=a_{1}-ia_{2}+a_{1}+ia_{2}=2a_{1}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ a_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{X}_{12}+\hat{X}_{21}\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
On the other hand, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\hat{X}_{12}+\hat{X}_{21}=-a_{1}+ia_{2}-a_{1}+ia_{2}=2ia_{2}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ a_{2}=\frac{1}{2i}\left(\hat{X}_{21}-\hat{X}_{12}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
And finally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}$
\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{X}_{11}-\hat{X}_{22}=a_{0}+a_{3}-a_{0}+a_{3}=2a_{3}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ a_{3}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\hat{X}_{11}-\hat{X}_{22}\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Problem*
Using the rules of bra-ket algebra, prove or evaluate the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $tr(XY)=tr(YX)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are operators; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(XY)^{\dagger}=Y^{\dagger}X^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are operators; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $exp[if(A)]=?$
\end_inset

 in ket-bra form, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a Hermitian operator whose eigenvalues are known; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a^{\prime}}\psi^{\prime*}(x^{\prime})\psi^{\prime}(x^{\prime\prime})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\prime}(x^{\prime})=\langle x^{\prime}|a^{\prime}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
For 1), we have that in general, any operator can be expressed in a matrix
 form in the following way
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\rightarrow A_{ij}=\langle i|A|j\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

and moreover, by definition, the trace of the operator is given by the following
 expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(A)=\sum_{i}A_{ii}=\sum_{i}\langle i|A|i\rangle
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $XY$
\end_inset

 in matrix notation can be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
XY\rightarrow\left(XY\right)_{ij}=X_{ik}Y_{kj},
\]

\end_inset

 therefore, the trace of the previous operator will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}\left(XY\right)_{ii}=\sum_{i}X_{ik}Y_{ki}=\sum_{i}\sum_{k}\langle i|X|k\rangle\langle k|Y|i\rangle=\sum_{k}\sum_{i}\langle k|Y|i\rangle\langle i|X|k\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where we've used that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k}|k\rangle\langle k|=\sum_{k}|i\rangle\langle i|=1,
\]

\end_inset

thus, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}\left(XY\right)_{ii}=\sum_{k}\sum_{i}\langle k|Y|i\rangle\langle i|X|k\rangle=\sum_{k}\langle k|YX|k\rangle=\sum_{i}\left(YX\right)_{ii},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we end up with the following expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tr(XY)=tr(YX).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now, for 2) we have that in general, the dual correspondence between an
 operator can be expressed in the following way 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X|\alpha\rangle\Longleftrightarrow_{DC}\langle\alpha|X^{\dagger},
\]

\end_inset

and in order to make realy explicit, for two operators we'll use the following
 notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(Y|\alpha\rangle\right)=X|\beta\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

and by the dual correspondence, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X|\beta\rangle\Longleftrightarrow_{DC}\langle\beta|X^{\dagger},
\]

\end_inset

but the bra 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\beta|$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\beta|=\langle\alpha|Y^{\dagger},
\]

\end_inset

by simply using the dual correspondence again.
 Therefore, we have the following result 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\left(Y|\alpha\rangle\right)\Longleftrightarrow_{DC}\langle\alpha|Y^{\dagger}X^{\dagger},
\]

\end_inset

on in terms of the notation used in the statement of the problem,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(XY\right)^{\dagger}=Y^{\dagger}X^{\dagger}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
For 3) we know that, we can expand the exponential function as an infinite
 sum in the following way
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp(x)=\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}x^{n},
\]

\end_inset

and using the same line of thought, for the expression at hand, we have
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp\left(if\left(A\right)\right)=\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}\left(if\left(A\right)\right)^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Now, if we use a matrix representation of the above operator, we have that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha_{i}|\exp\left(if\left(A\right)\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}\left(if\left(A\right)\right)^{n}|\alpha_{j}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 can be expanded as a Taylor serie, in the following way 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(A\right)=\sum_{n}\frac{f^{n}}{n!}A^{n},
\]

\end_inset

and if we follow the same procedure and use a matrix representation, we
 have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha_{i}|f\left(A\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|\sum_{n}\frac{f^{n}}{n!}A^{n}|\alpha_{j}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

but by assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is Hermitian and its eigenvalues are known, therefore, we can say that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A|\alpha_{j}\rangle=a_{j}|\alpha_{j}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

and with that, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha_{i}|f\left(A\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|\sum_{n}\frac{f^{n}}{n!}A^{n}|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|\sum_{n}\frac{f^{n}}{n!}\alpha_{j}^{n}|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|f\left(\alpha_{j}\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\langle\alpha_{i}|f\left(A\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|f\left(\alpha_{j}\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle.
\]

\end_inset

And using that previous results, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha_{i}|\exp\left(if\left(A\right)\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\langle\alpha_{i}|\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}\left(if\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\right)^{n}|\alpha_{j}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\langle\alpha_{i}|\exp\left(if\left(A\right)\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}i^{n}f^{n}\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\langle\alpha_{i}|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}i^{n}f^{n}\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\delta_{ij},
\]

\end_inset

but, in the rhd of the last expression, we do the following identification
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}i^{n}f^{n}\left(\alpha_{j}\right)=\exp\left(if\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

 therefore, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\langle\alpha_{i}|\exp\left(if\left(A\right)\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle=\exp\left(if\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\right)\delta_{ij},
\]

\end_inset

and finally we know that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as an outer product of the elements of the basis, thus,
 we end with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
exp[if(A)]=\sum_{\alpha_{j}}\exp\left(if\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\right)|\alpha_{j}\rangle\langle\alpha_{j}|.
\]

\end_inset

It's important to notice that in all the previous calculations, the matrix
 notation was performed in terms of the eigenbase of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Finally, for part 4), we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a^{\prime}}\psi^{\prime*}(x^{\prime})\psi^{\prime}(x^{\prime\prime})=\sum_{a^{\prime}}\langle x^{\prime}|a^{\prime}\rangle\langle a^{\prime}|x^{\prime\prime}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

but, using the completeness relationship, which states that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{a^{\prime}}|a^{\prime}\rangle\langle a^{\prime}|=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a^{\prime}}\psi^{\prime*}(x^{\prime})\psi^{\prime}(x^{\prime\prime})=\langle x^{\prime}|x^{\prime\prime}\rangle=\delta(x^{\prime}-x^{\prime\prime}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{a^{\prime}}\psi^{\prime*}(x^{\prime})\psi^{\prime}(x^{\prime\prime})=\delta(x^{\prime}-x^{\prime\prime}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem*
\paragraph_spacing single
Construct 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}}|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle=\frac{\hbar}{2}|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by the angles shown in the figure.
 Express your answer as a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $|+\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|-\rangle$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem*
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename FigProblem.jpg
	scale 15

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Figure of problem 1.11
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Let's write the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

 as function of the angles given, which is clear it's going to be the usual
 expression for a vector in terms of spherical coordinates,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{\hat{n}}=\sin(\alpha)\cos(\alpha)\hat{\mathbf{x}}+\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)\hat{\mathbf{y}}+\cos(\beta)\mathbf{\hat{z}}\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then, the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}\cdot\mathbf{\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}=S_{x}\sin(\alpha)\cos(\alpha)+S_{y}\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)+S_{z}\cos(\beta)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, we know that in matrix notation the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{x},S_{y},S_{z}$
\end_inset

, in the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{z}$
\end_inset

 basis, are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{x}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right),\ S_{y}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{array}\right)\ \text{y}\ S_{z}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
thus, the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

, in matrix notation is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\sin(\beta)\cos(\alpha)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right)+\frac{\hbar}{2}\sin(\beta)\sin(\alpha)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -i\\
i & 0
\end{array}\right)+\frac{\hbar}{2}\cos(\beta)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos(\beta) & \sin(\beta)\cos(\alpha)-i\sin(\beta)\sin(\alpha)\\
\sin(\beta)\cos(\alpha)+i\sin(\beta)\sin(\alpha) & -\cos(\beta)
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos(\beta) & \sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)\\
\sin(\beta)\exp(i\alpha) & -\cos(\beta)
\end{array}\right)\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we must construct 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle$
\end_inset

 such that the following equation holds 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos(\beta) & \sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)\\
\sin(\beta)\exp(i\alpha) & -\cos(\beta)
\end{array}\right)|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle=\frac{\hbar}{2}|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle,\label{eq:08}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
but we can express the ket 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the basis kets 
\begin_inset Formula $|+\rangle$
\end_inset

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $|-\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, let's we want to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{+}\text{,}\mathcal{C}_{-}\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle=\mathcal{C}_{+}|+\rangle+\mathcal{C}_{-}|-\rangle\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or, in matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\\
\mathcal{C}_{-}
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, and with this, the equation given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reads 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos(\beta) & \sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)\\
\sin(\beta)\exp(i\alpha) & -\cos(\beta)
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\\
\mathcal{C}_{-}
\end{array}\right)=\frac{\hbar}{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\\
\mathcal{C}_{-}
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\cos(\beta)+\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)\\
\mathcal{C}_{+}\sin(\beta)\exp(i\alpha)-\mathcal{C}_{-}\cos(\beta)
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\\
\mathcal{C}_{-}
\end{array}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then, we have the following equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\cos(\beta)+\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)=\mathcal{C}_{+},\label{eq:09}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{C}_{+}\sin(\beta)\exp(i\alpha)-\mathcal{C}_{-}\cos(\beta)=\mathcal{C}_{-}.\label{eq:10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before moving on with the calculations, lets remember that the ket 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle$
\end_inset

 should be normalized, and this condition, translates into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \langle+;\mathbf{S\cdot\hat{n}}|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle\right\Vert =\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}+\mathcal{C}_{-}^{2}=1\text{.}\label{eq:11}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's play a little with the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{+}\cos(\beta)+\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)=\mathcal{C}_{+}\implies\mathcal{C}_{+}\left(1-\cos(\beta)\right)=\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and, remember, in general 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{+}\text{,}\mathcal{C}_{-}\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, therefor, if we multiply by its complex conjugate, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\left(1-\cos(\beta)\right)^{2}=\mathcal{C}_{-}^{2}\sin^{2}(\beta).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, if we use the following trigonometric identity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{2}(\beta/2)=1/2\left(1-\cos(\beta)\right)$
\end_inset

, and the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{-}^{2}=1-\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
4\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\sin^{4}(\beta/2)=\left(1-\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\right)\sin^{2}(\beta)\text{.}\label{eq:12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's use the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(\theta)\cos(\phi)=1/2(\sin(\theta+\phi)+\sin(\theta-\phi))$
\end_inset

 with the changes given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\beta/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\beta/2$
\end_inset

, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sin\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\sin\left(\beta\right)+\sin(0)\right)\implies\sin\left(\beta\right)=2\sin\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\sin^{2}\left(\beta\right)=4\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if we subsitute the previous result in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:12"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\sin^{4}(\beta/2)=4\left(1-\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\right)\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\left(1-\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\right)\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\implies\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)+\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\ \mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}\left(\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)+\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\right)=\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\implies\mathcal{C}_{+}^{2}=\cos^{2}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\ \mathcal{C}_{+}=\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, for the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{-}$
\end_inset

, as in the previous case, let's look at the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, from which we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta)\exp(-i\alpha)=\mathcal{C}_{+}\left(1-\cos\left(\beta\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And using the relationship before shown 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin^{2}\left(\beta/2\right)=1/2\left(1-\cos(\beta)\right)$
\end_inset

 y 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(\beta\right)=2\sin(\beta/2)\cos(\beta/2)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\mathcal{C}_{-}\sin(\beta/2)\cos(\beta/2)\exp(-i\alpha)=2\mathcal{C}_{+}\sin^{2}\left(\beta/2\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\mathcal{C}_{-}\cos(\beta/2)\exp(-i\alpha)=\mathcal{C}_{+}\sin\left(\beta/2\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
but, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{+}=\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{C}_{-}\cos(\beta/2)\exp(-i\alpha)=\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\sin\left(\beta/2\right),\implies\mathcal{C}_{-}\exp(-i\alpha)=\sin\left(\beta/2\right)\text{,}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\therefore\ \mathcal{C}_{-}=\sin\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\exp(i\alpha)\label{eq:13}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the ket 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle$
\end_inset

 written in terms if the basis kets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ |+\rangle,|-\rangle\right\} $
\end_inset

 its given by
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\mathbf{S}\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}};+\rangle=\cos\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)|+\rangle+\sin\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\exp(i\alpha)|-\rangle\text{.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem*
The Hamiltonian operator for a two-state system is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=a\left(|1\rangle\langle1|-|2\rangle\langle2|+|1\rangle\langle2|+|2\rangle\langle1|\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a number with the dimensions of energy.
 Find the energy eigenvalues and the corresponding energy eigenkets (as
 linear combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Let's fix a basis, and let be 
\begin_inset Formula $|1\rangle=(1,0)^{T}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|2\rangle=(0,1)^{T}$
\end_inset

, therefore, the Hamiltonian, expressed in terms of this basis is given
 by the following matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=a\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and for ehe eigenvalues and eigenvectors, we have to solve the following
 eigenvalue problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H|\alpha\rangle=\lambda|\alpha\rangle\label{eq:EigenValueProblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha\rangle$
\end_inset

, which can also be stated in the following way 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(H-\lambda\mathbb{I}\right)|\alpha\rangle=0$
\end_inset

, and the problem can be translated into the following
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(H-\lambda\mathbb{I}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left(H-\lambda\mathbb{I}\right)=0\iff\det\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a-\lambda & a\\
a & -a-\lambda
\end{array}\right)=0\iff-\left(a-\lambda\right)\left(a+\lambda\right)-a^{2}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iff a^{2}-\lambda^{2}+a^{2}=0\iff\lambda^{2}=2a^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
and then, we have that the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\pm}=\pm\sqrt{2}a.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now, for the eigenvectors we have to solve the eigenvalue problem given
 in the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EigenValueProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for any of the eigenvalues given in the previous equation.
 If we plug 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{_{\pm}}=\pm\sqrt{2}a$
\end_inset

, and take 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha\rangle=(x_{1},x_{2})^{T}$
\end_inset

, and then we end with the following system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
\left(a\pm\sqrt{2}a\right)x_{1}+ax_{2}=\sqrt{2}ax_{1}\\
ax_{1}+\left(-a\pm\sqrt{2}a\right)x_{2}=\sqrt{2}ax_{2}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

which can be solved by the conventional methods at hand.
 Giving the following eigenkets, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\alpha_{+}\rangle=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1-\sqrt{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{-}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\alpha_{-}\rangle=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1+\sqrt{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

And finally, if we normalize the previous kets, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\hat{\alpha}_{+}\rangle=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{1-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1-\sqrt{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\hat{\alpha}_{-}\rangle=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{1+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1+\sqrt{2}\\
1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

